NUMA (Non-Uniform Memory Access) – Quick Notes

- Definition:
    - NUMA is a computer memory design used in multiprocessor systems.
    - In NUMA, a processor (CPU) accesses its local memory faster than non-local memory (memory local to another CPU).

- Structure:
    - System is divided into NUMA nodes.
    - Each NUMA node contains:
        - One or more CPU cores
        - Local memory
        - Interconnects to other NUMA nodes

- Memory:
    - Each NUMA node has its own physically attached memory.
    - Global memory is still accessible, but access latency varies:
        - Local memory: low latency
        - Remote memory (another NUMA node): higher latency

- Reason for existence:
    - Improves scalability of multiprocessor systems.
    - Reduces memory access bottlenecks compared to uniform shared memory (UMA).
    - Helps high-performance applications like HFT reduce latency by using local memory.

- Key points for HFT/Performance:
    - Place frequently used data on the same NUMA node as the CPU processing it.
    - Avoid cross-node memory access in latency-sensitive applications.
    - Tools like `numactl` can control memory/CPU allocation per NUMA node.

- Diagram (conceptual):

    [CPU0] -- Local Memory0
        \
         \
      Interconnect
         \
          [CPU1] -- Local Memory1

- Summary:
    - NUMA = multiple CPU+memory clusters (nodes)
    - Local memory is faster, remote memory is slower
    - Optimizing for NUMA reduces latency



Memory Management & Access – UMA vs NUMA

    - Key Components:

        - MMU (Memory Management Unit):
            - Translates virtual addresses to physical addresses.
            - Works with page tables and manages memory access permissions.

        - TLB (Translation Lookaside Buffer):
            - Cache inside the MMU for recent virtual->physical translations.
            - Speeds up address translation, reduces page table access latency.

        - Memory Controller:
            - Interfaces CPU with memory.
            - Handles read/write requests, refresh cycles, and scheduling.

        - TLP (Thread-Level Parallelism) [Optional]:
            - Running multiple threads in parallel on CPU cores.
            - Utilization depends on memory access efficiency (local vs remote).

    - Uniform Memory Access (UMA) Systems:
        - All CPUs share a single global memory.
        - Memory access latency is uniform for all CPUs.
        - Interaction:
            - MMU + TLB handle virtual->physical translation for all CPUs.
            - Central memory controller handles all read/write requests.
            - High TLP can cause contention at the memory controller.
        - Diagram (conceptual):

            [CPU0] \
            [CPU1]  --> [MMU+TLB] --> [Memory Controller] --> [Global Memory]
            [CPU2] /

    - Non-Uniform Memory Access (NUMA) Systems:
        - Memory is physically distributed across NUMA nodes.
        - Access latency depends on local vs remote memory.
        - Interaction:
            - Each NUMA node has its own MMU + TLB and Memory Controller.
            - MMU + TLB handle translations for local memory.
            - Memory Controller manages local memory access.
            - Interconnect is used for remote memory access.
            - TLP should be optimized to use local memory to reduce latency.
        - Diagram (conceptual):

            [CPU0] -- [MMU+TLB] -- [Memory Controller] --> Local Memory0
                \
                 \
              Interconnect
                 \
                  [CPU1] -- [MMU+TLB] -- [Memory Controller] --> Local Memory1

    - Key Differences:
        - UMA:
            - Single memory controller, same latency for all CPUs.
            - Simple architecture, can bottleneck at high TLP.
        - NUMA:
            - Distributed memory controllers, latency varies.
            - Optimizing for local memory access improves performance.

